03995nam a22006735i 9780292784857DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212010txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927848577 a10.7560/7219992doi  a(DE-B1597)588246  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aGV415 ǂb H66 2010eb 7aPHO0230602bisacsh04a796.332620976400aHome Field :bTexas High School Football Stadiums from Alice to Zephyr /ced. by Bobby Hawthorne. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2010  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tFOREWORD BY BUZZ BISSINGER -- tTHE STADIUMS -- tAFTERWORD -- tAKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tA-Z STADIUM INDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"The promise of an empty football field is an irresistible force for those who understand and revere the game," Jeff Wilson observes. Drawn by the sense of possibility and nostalgia inherent in every stadium, Wilson traveled the state of Texas to photograph high school stadiums for a photo essay that appeared in Texas Monthly in August 2005. The magazine's readers responded with an outpouring of enthusiasm, and Wilson's photo essay was nominated for a prestigious National Magazine Award. In Home Field, Wilson creates a unique photo portrait of nearly eighty Texas high school football stadiums, ranging from the bright lights, artificial turf, and seating for thousands at Southlake Carroll to the lone set of bleachers under the wide open sky in Veribest. Shot from the fifty-yard line facing the home stands, these photographs invite us to view each stadium from the same vantage point and experience it as an evocative place that holds a community's collective memories. Accompanying the photographs are reminiscences about the fields from players, coaches, team physicians, athletic directors, sportswriters and announcers, school superintendents, principals and teachers, band directors, maintenance workers, booster club parents, students, and fans. Their stories—whether funny, nostalgic, or poignant—reveal just how important high school football is to Texans and how it creates an unforgettable sense of community and camaraderie. Sure to bring back memories as soon as you open the book, Home Field captures what football is supposed to be—"simple and pure, like a perfect spiral arcing gracefully across the sky."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aPhotography / Subjects & Themes / Sports.2bisacsh1 aBissinger, Buzz.1 aHawthorne, Bobby, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWilson, Jeff, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilson, Jeff.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292784857423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292784857/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK